         <div type="translation">
            <p><choice corresp="#a1"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:carling2000"/><citedRange>310</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">Thereupon, the bodhisattva Maitreya, although still young and small in years (with his hands) adorned with webbings, glorious,</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a2"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">(he took a gold-colored leaf) ... by the putting down (a line) he writes thousand akṣaras. Thereupon, having given this leaf to his father, he says: ... </seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a3"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:carling2000"/><citedRange>403</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">These akṣara writings in this kind of configuration, these are the characters fashioned by the sages. But for our sake, who are illuminating the speech appropriate for the nirvāṇa,</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a4"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1983"/><citedRange>35</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">these characters do not count as the (proper) script. Being astonished and amazed, Brahmāyu says: " Which script then counts as the [proper] script?" || Thereupon, the bodhisattva ... </seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a5"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1954"/><citedRange>743</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:knoll1996"/><citedRange>28, 42, 46</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">This script is definitely appropriate to make known all the Laws. Therefore</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a6"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">this script counts as the proper script. These characters are comparable by the configuration but it does not exist here in the world. Then the god Brahmā stands in the sky ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a7"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">Among all characters, these characters are the glorious ones, (which were written by the Buddhas) as numerous as the grains of sand of the Gaṅgā-river.</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b2"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... Having heard that(, the purohita Brahmāyu says:) ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b3"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... (this) script stands. || Then the purohita says to the bodhisattva: "O lord, ..."</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b4"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1981"/><citedRange>490</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... (the bodhisattva say)s: Hear, o father! || In the tune Niṣkramānta: || From Ratnaśikhin onwards until Śākyamuni</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b5"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1995"/><citedRange>67</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:kolver1965"/><citedRange>18</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">many Buddha-gods, teachers, (to many gods and mortals by the ten thousands, by the thousands,) by the hundreds, the ones who have attained the realm of script,</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b6"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">these ones were the teachers of the (proper) script, from them I have learned to write this script and writing named Brāhmī. Having heard that the purohita Brahmāyu with great respect ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b7"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... having gathered (his disciples) with both hands in añjali, he says to the venerable Maitreya: ||</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b8"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... in the script and writing there is no other one equal to you. (I entrust you with) [my] 84,000 (disciples.)</seg></seg></choice></p>
         </div>
         <div type="comments">
            <p><note type="parallels">MaitrHami 11, 14b 23-16a 16</note><note type="philcomment">This fragment contains part of the eleventh act of the Maitreyasamitināṭaka; an Uy. parallel is MaitrHami 11, 14b23-16a16. See also <bibl><title corresp="ref:pinault1999"/><citedRange>199-200</citedRange></bibl>.</note><note type="remarks">Fragment of a manuscript which includes A 251 - A 294 (cf. <bibl><title corresp="ref:gengetal2004a"/><citedRange>64-65</citedRange></bibl>). Lines a7-8 and b1-2 are lost.</note><note type="remarks">For a full translation and commentary cf. <bibl><title corresp="ref:pinault2013"/><citedRange>210-227</citedRange></bibl>.</note><note corresp="#a3" type="philcomment">Beginning of a stanza of 4x12 (5/7).</note><note corresp="#b8" type="philcomment">Beginning of a stanza of 4x12 (5/7).</note></p>
