               <item n="m_translation_old">a1 Thereupon, the bodhisattva Maitreya, although still young and small in years (with his hands) adorned with webbings, glorious,
a2 (he took a gold-colored leaf) ... by the putting down (a line) he writes thousand akṣaras. Thereupon, having given this leaf to his father, he says: ... 
a3 These akṣara writings in this kind of configuration, these are the characters fashioned by the sages. But for our sake, who are illuminating the speech appropriate for the nirvāṇa,
a4 these characters do not count as the (proper) script. Being astonished and amazed, Brahmāyu says: " Which script then counts as the [proper] script?" || Thereupon, the bodhisattva ... 
a5 This script is definitely appropriate to make known all the Laws. Therefore
a6 this script counts as the proper script. These characters are comparable by the configuration but it does not exist here in the world. Then the god Brahmā stands in the sky ...
a7 Among all characters, these characters are the glorious ones, (which were written by the Buddhas) as numerous as the grains of sand of the Gaṅgā-river.
b2 ... Having heard that(, the purohita Brahmāyu says:) ...
b3 ... (this) script stands. || Then the purohita says to the bodhisattva: "O lord, ..."
b4 ... (the bodhisattva say)s: Hear, o father! || In the tune Niṣkramānta: || From Ratnaśikhin onwards until Śākyamuni
b5 many Buddha-gods, teachers, (to many gods and mortals by the ten thousands, by the thousands,) by the hundreds, the ones who have attained the realm of script,
b6 these ones were the teachers of the (proper) script, from them I have learned to write this script and writing named Brāhmī. Having heard that the purohita Brahmāyu with great respect ...
b7 ... having gathered (his disciples) with both hands in añjali, he says to the venerable Maitreya: ||
b8 ... in the script and writing there is no other one equal to you. (I entrust you with) [my] 84,000 (disciples.)</item>
